RFC 001: Async Dispatch-Wait Protocol for Agentic LLMs
Version: 1.0.0
Status: Proposed Standard
Date: June 28, 2026
Author: Paul Tretter
Category: Model Architecture / Agentic Infrastructure
1. Abstract
The Async Dispatch-Wait Protocol introduces a deterministic suspension and resumption mechanism for Large Language Model (LLM) inference engines. By elevating the await paradigm from the application layer to a native model-level execution state, this protocol allows sub-agents to explicitly yield execution control without hallucinating results, looping, or engaging in token-heavy polling behaviors. Execution is strictly blocked and KV cache state is preserved until a cryptographically signed dispatch_hash is returned, ensuring optimal token expenditure and deterministic state management in multi-agent systems.
2. Motivation
Current agentic frameworks treat LLMs as stateless request/response endpoints. When an agent encounters a long-running external dependency (e.g., a sub-agent task, human-in-the-loop approval, or slow API), the application layer manages the state. This architectural mismatch results in two critical failures:
The Polling Tax: Orchestrators repeatedly prompt the LLM to check status, regenerating the entire context window and wasting massive amounts of compute and tokens.
The "Last Word" Hallucination: LLMs are autoregressive; they are mathematically compelled to produce a completion. When forced to wait, they often hallucinate tool outputs, simulate the next steps, or enter infinite reasoning loops to satisfy the autoregressive objective.
The Dispatch-Wait Protocol solves this by treating suspension as a native model-level execution state, effectively providing the yield and await keywords for LLM inference.
3. Specification Goals and Non-Goals
Goals
Determinism: Strictly prevent the model from hallucinating or simulating the outcomes of awaited tasks.
Zero-Token Waiting: Eliminate the polling tax; a suspended model consumes exactly zero tokens while waiting.
Resumable Context: Preserve the exact computational state (KV Cache) so resumption requires no re-evaluation of prior context.
Cryptographic Integrity: Ensure routing and state transitions are secure against injection and spoofing.
Non-Goals
General State Management: This protocol does not replace standard application state databases (e.g., Redis) for non-LLM workflow steps.
Cross-Vendor KV Portability: This spec assumes a homogeneous model environment; it does not define a standard for moving KV caches between different model architectures (e.g., Llama to Mistral).
