11. Ecosystem Positioning & Path to Adoption
The Dispatch-Wait Protocol is not merely a feature; it is the missing primitive for the Agentic OS. Just as TCP/IP provided reliable packets, and HTTP provided request/response, Dispatch-Wait provides reliable, stateful, asynchronous agentic execution.
Implementation Strategy
To achieve adoption similar to the Model Context Protocol (MCP), the following steps are required:
Target Inference Engine Maintainers: The application layer (LangChain, CrewAI) cannot implement this alone. We must engage the maintainers of vLLM, SGLang, and llama.cpp to build native support for KV cache serialization/deserialization tied to a routing hash.
Proof of Concept (PoC): A reference implementation must be built using an engine that already supports KV cache offloading (e.g., SGLang's RadixAttention). A side-by-side token comparison (Standard Polling Agent vs. Dispatch-Wait Agent) will provide the empirical cost-savings metric required to drive adoption.
12. Future Extensions
Nested Dispatch (DAG Execution): Allowing a suspended sub-agent to itself dispatch a sub-task, creating a Directed Acyclic Graph of suspended contexts. The inference engine will manage a stack of KV caches.
Distributed Dispatchers: Sharding frozen KV caches across a cluster of inference nodes, allowing a sub-agent suspended on Node A to be resumed on Node B (requires standardized KV cache serialization formats).
